    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Lazurite is a tectosilicate mineral with sulfate, $(l:ores/Sulfur)sulfur$(/l) and chloride with formula: (Na,Ca)8[(S,Cl,SO4,OH)2|(Al6Si6O24)]. It is a feldspathoid and a member of the $(l:ores/Sodalite)sodalite$(/l) group. Lazurite crystallizes in the isometric system although well formed crystals are rare. It is usually massive and forms the bulk of the gemstone $(l:ores/Lapis)lapis$(/l) lazuli.$(p)Lazurite is a deep blue to greenish blue. The colour is due to the presence of S−"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "3 anions. It has a Mohs hardness of 5.0 to 5.5 and a specific gravity of 2.4. It is translucent with a refractive index of 1.50. It is fusible at 3.5 on Wolfgang Franz von Kobell's fusibility scale, and soluble in HCl. It commonly contains or is associated with grains of $(l:ores/Pyrite)pyrite$(/l).$(p)Lazurite is a product of contact metamorphism of limestone and typically is associated with $(l:ores/Calcite)calcite$(/l), $(l:ores/Pyrite)pyrite$(/l), diopside, humite, "
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "forsterite, hauyne and muscovite.$(p)Other blue minerals such as the carbonate azurite and the $(l:ores/Phosphate)phosphate$(/l) lazulite may be confused with lazurite, but are easily distinguished with careful examination. Lazurite at one time was used as a synonym for azurite.$(p)Lazurite was first described in 1890 for an occurrence in the Sar-e-Sang District, Koksha Valley, "
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Badakhshan Province, Afghanistan. It has been mined for over 6,000 years in the $(l:ores/Lapis)lapis$(/l) lazuli district of Badakhshan, Afghanistan. It has been used as a pigment in painting and cloth dyeing since at least the sixth or seventh century CE. It is also mined at Lake Baikal in Siberia; Mount Vesuvius; Burma; Canada; and the United States. The name is from the Persian lazward for blue."
    }
